    <title>big questions and the best of 2012</title>
    <content type='html'>&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;"&gt;
&lt;a href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEjkiwGlHajQEoYyGbGWw6neqfWKCUudwUJibdcFsIKZnN-TH0oEySyIDxSjFsuHxXPofh__RmQVQC1UCwlHFdlL4ia9tjhAEISQI9xdDLR7Tl_9GRhiUfxqYVQXHjdK5LN92ItcEgvlzLw/s1600/j9821.gif" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;"&gt;&lt;img border="0" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEjkiwGlHajQEoYyGbGWw6neqfWKCUudwUJibdcFsIKZnN-TH0oEySyIDxSjFsuHxXPofh__RmQVQC1UCwlHFdlL4ia9tjhAEISQI9xdDLR7Tl_9GRhiUfxqYVQXHjdK5LN92ItcEgvlzLw/s1600/j9821.gif" height="320" width="207" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;"&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: left;"&gt;
Another installment in Mircea Pitici's annual collection of the best popular writing in mathematics is available from Princeton . Like its predecessor (see this post for a brief review of last year's collection &lt;a href="http://www.mathrecreation.com/2012/01/best-of-2011.html"&gt;here&lt;/a&gt;), its an excellent selection of accessible, enjoyable, and useful writing about many aspects of mathematics.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: left;"&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: left;"&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: left;"&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both;"&gt;
verything that Tim Gowers writes is worth reading, or trying to read, and you can http://gowers.wordpress.com/&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both;"&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both;"&gt;
By his own report he was reluctant to write the piece on X&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both;"&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both;"&gt;
If this overview did anything, it put me in the right frame of mind to read Robert Lang's piece, which, I think, has forever settled the question of "invention vs. discovery" for me, and did so by completely refuting the grounds on which this false dichotomy stands.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both;"&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both;"&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both;"&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both;"&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both;"&gt;
Robert Lang's piece stands out as fitting in to the 'popular mathematics' category for its subject matter (the mathematics of paper folding) rather than for its lack of technical details. For he does get technical in describing work on flat-unfoldability - a set of conditions that describe what flat patterns (origami tesselations) can be unfolded into a crease pattern. The notion of flat-unfoldability is complementary to the the notion of flat-foldability, a set of conditions that describe whether a crease pattern can be folded into a flat shape. Lang sums up his work with these lines:&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both;"&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both;"&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both;"&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both;"&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both;"&gt;
And there it is. Mathematical work is not an exercise in the archeology of platonic ideals, nor is it the tinkering in a workshop to invent new objects. Mathematical labour is not about static things - it is dynamic: it is about the expansion of possibilities. It is about actions, not objects: mathematics expands the horizons of what can be done. I think this helps to explain part of the appeal for both the recreational and the professional mathematician - the amature who does math for themselves is expanding the potential of what they can do, while the professional is expanding the horizon of a whole mathematical community.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both;"&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both;"&gt;
